{"cursor":"31449","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{multiple issues|\n\n\n\n}}\n\n\n'Business process improvement' ('BPI') is a systematic approach to help an\norganization optimize its underlying processes to achieve more efficient\nresults. The methodology was first documented in H. James Harringtonâs 1991\nbook Business Process Improvement. [http://www.amazon.com/dp/0070267685 Business Process\nImprovement] (ISBN 978-0070267688) It is the methodology that both\nProcess Redesign and Business Process Reengineering are based upon. BPI has\nbeen responsible for reducing cost and cycle time by as much as 90% while\nimproving quality by over 60%.\n\n'Process improvement' is an aspect of organizational development (OD) in which a\nseries of actions are taken by a process owner to identify, analyze and improve\nexisting business processes within an organization to meet new goals and\nobjectives, ISBN 0-566-07633-0 such as increasing\nprofits and performance, reducing costs and accelerating schedules. These actions often follow a specific\nmethodology or strategy to encourage and ultimately create successful\nresults. Process improvement may include the\nrestructuring of company training programs to increase their effectiveness.\n\nProcess improvement is also a method to introduce process changes to improve the\nquality of a product or service, to better match customer and consumer\nneeds.\n","linknr":315,"url":"Process_improvement","recorded":1371228521,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Business_process_improvement&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Business_process_improvement&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","/wiki/Business_process_improvement","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharins